The '''military–industrial–media complex''' is an offshoot of the [[military–industrial complex]]. Organizations like [[Fairness and Accuracy in Reporting]] have accused the military industrial media complex of using their media resources to promote militarism, which, according to Fairness and Accuracy in Reporting's hypothesis, benefits the defense resources of the company and allows for a controlled narrative of armed conflicts. In this way, media coverage can be manipulated to show increased effectiveness of weapons systems and to avoid covering civilian casualties, or reducing the emphasis on them. Examples of such coverage include that of the [[Gulf War|Persian Gulf War]], [[NATO bombing of Yugoslavia]] and the [[Iraq War]].<ref name="vfair">{{cite web|url=https://fair.org/extra/the-military-industrial-media-complex/|title=The Military-Industrial-Media Complex|last=Solomon|first=Norman|authorlink=Norman Solomon|date=July–August 2005|work=[[Extra!]]|publisher=''[[Fairness and Accuracy in Reporting]]''|accessdate=2008-12-19}}</ref> It is a common practice by defense contractors and weapons systems manufacturers to hire former military personnel as media spokespersons<ref name="nyt" />. In 2008, the New York Times found that aproximately 75 military analysts - many with military industry ties - were being investigated by the [[Government Accountability Office]] and other federal organizations for taking part in a years long campaign to influence them into becoming "surrogates" for the [[Presidency of George W. Bush|Bush administration]]'s military policy in the media <ref name="nyt" />.

== Gulf War ==
[[General Electric]] is a subcontractor for the [[Tomahawk cruise missile]] and [[Patriot missile|Patriot II missile]], both of which were used extensively during the [[Gulf War|Persian Gulf War]].<ref name="vfair" /> . General Electric also manufactures components for the [[Northrop Grumman B-2 Spirit|B-2 stealth bomber]] and [[Boeing B-52 Stratofortress|B-52 bomber]] and the [[E-3 AWACS]] aircraft which were also used extensively during the conflict. During the first [[Gulf War]], General Electric received $2 billion in defense contracts related to weapons which would be used in Gulf War and [[Operation Enduring Freedom|the 2003 invasion and subsequent occupation of Iraq]] by [[Coalition of the willing|Coalition Forces]]. As FAIR observed, "when correspondents and paid consultants on NBC television praised the performance of U.S. weapons, they were extolling equipment made by GE, the corporation that pays their salaries."<ref name="vfair" />

== NATO bombing of Yugoslavia ==
During the [[NATO bombing of Yugoslavia]], media coverage specifically avoided mentioning civilian casualties, even when mentioning the bombing of civilian targets such as infrastructure. <ref name="vfair" />  Media coverage relied extensively on official NATO government and military sources for reporting, and repeatedly talked about current and future weaponry of NATO in favorable and expectant terms. <ref name="vfair" /> 

== Iraq War ==
Media-Military coordination was such that media executives met in the [[The Pentagon|Pentagon]] with military officials to decide what to cover and how. <ref name="vfair" /> In 2007, a company named Defense Solutions hired former four-star general and [[NBC]] analyst [[Barry_McCaffrey|Barry McCaffrey]] to petition [[David Petraeus]] to buy 5000 armored vehicles from Defense Solutions<ref name = "nyt">{{cite news |last1=Barstow |first1=David |title=One Man’s Military-Industrial-Media Complex |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/30/washington/30general.html |accessdate=1 November 2018 |language=en}}</ref>. Subsequently, McCaffrey appeared on [[CNBC]] and praised Petraeus. The next month he encouraged congress in public testimony to purchase more armored vehicles, and criticized a plan that would see the purchase of vehicles from a competitor of Defense Solutions <ref name="nyt" />. 

